==Old English==

===Alternative spellings===
* [[īw]], [[ēow]], [[eoh|ēoh]]

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*īwa-'', from Indo-European ''*eiwo-'', a suffixed form of the base ''*ei-'' ‘reddish, colourful’.  Cognate with Old High German [[iwa|īwa]] (German [[Eibe]]), Middle Low German [[iwe|īwe]] (Dutch [[ijf]]), Old Norse [[yr|ýr]] ‘bow, yew’.  The IE root is perhaps also the source of Old Irish ''ēo'' (Irish [[iúr]]), Baltic ''*eiwa-'' (Lithuanian [[ieva|ievà]]), Slavic ''*jiva'' (Russian [[ива]] ‘willow’), Latin [[uva|ūva]] ‘bunch of grapes’.

The West Germanic languages have a variant (''*īxwa-'') with a guttural consonant, represented by Old English [[eoh|ēoh]].

